Creating a full-fledged ascii-based tower defense game here would be too extensive, as it requires a substantial amount of code, far more than what fits into this format. However, I will provide you with a high-level outline and some sample code snippets that should get you started. You can then expand upon this according to your needs.

### Outline

Your game will require several key components:

1. **Game Initialization:** Setting up the game, creating the playing field, initializing game variables.
2. **Game Loop:** A continuous loop allowing the game to process player input, update game state, and render the game.
3. **Player:** Managing the player's position and actions.
4. **Gold Stashes:** Building and managing gold stashes.
5. **Zombies:** Spawning and moving zombies that attack the gold stashes.
6. **Day/Night Cycle:** Managing the transition between day and night.

Given these components, we'll start with creating the basics of these structures using classes in JavaScript. To keep it concise, I will limit the example to the initial game setup and a simplistic day/night cycle.

### HTML

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
<meta charset="UTF-8">
<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
<title>ASCII Tower Defense Game</title>
<link rel="stylesheet" href="styles.css">
</head>
<body>
<div id="game-container"></div>
<button id="play-button">Play</button>
<script src="game.js"></script>
</body>
</html>
```

### CSS (`styles.css`)

```css
body {
  font-family: 'Courier New', monospace;
  text-align: center;
}

#game-container {
  white-space: pre;
  font-size: 14px;
  line-height: 10px;
}

button {
  margin: 10px;
}
```

### JavaScript (`game.js`)

Here is a skeleton of the JS you'll need, using ES6 features and classes.

```javascript
class Game {
  constructor(containerId) {
    this.container = document.getElementById(containerId);
    this.grid = this.createGrid(10, 10);
    this.isDaytime = true;
    this.cycleDuration = 10000; // 10 seconds for demonstration
    this.startDayCycle();
  }

  createGrid(width, height) {
    return new Array(height).fill(null).map(() => new Array(width).fill('.'));
  }

  render() {
    this.container.textContent = this.grid.map(row => row.join(' ')).join('\n');
  }

  startDayCycle() {
    setInterval(() => {
      this.isDaytime = !this.isDaytime;
      // Nighttime actions like spawning zombies could go here
    }, this.cycleDuration);
  }
}

// Player
class Player {
  constructor(game) {
    this.game = game;
    this.x = Math.floor(Math.random() * this.game.grid[0].length);
    this.y = Math.floor(Math.random() * this.game.grid.length);
    this.sprite = '@';
    this.game.grid[this.y][this.x] = this.sprite;
  }

}

// Initialization
document.getElementById('play-button').addEventListener('click', () => {
  const game = new Game('game-container');
  const player = new Player(game);
  game.render();
});
```

This code sets up some of the classes you'll need, like `Game` and `Player`. It also provides methods for setting up the grid and rendering it. This includes creating the game grid and handling the day/night cycle with a periodic switch every 10 seconds.

You'll need to expand upon this to add methods that handle moving the player, placing and rendering gold stashes, spawning zombies, and the logic for zombies' movement and interactions with gold stashes. Also, implement proper display updates on each game tick and good algorithms for the AI of the zombies. Consider performance optimization and modularity as your game complexity grows.

Remember, even a simple ASCII tower defense game is a reasonably complex undertaking, so expect to write hundreds (if not thousands) of lines of code as you build out all these features. The code snippet provided here is just the starting point. Good luck with your programming endeavor!

All right, to add movement functionality for the player in the ASCII tower defense game, you'll need to handle keyboard input and update the player’s position accordingly. Below is an enhancement to the previous code that allows the player to move on the grid using the arrow keys. 

### JavaScript Movement Update (`game.js`)

```javascript
class Game {
  // ... existing code ...

  // Updates the rendering of the player's new position
  updatePlayerPosition(oldX, oldY, newX, newY) {
    this.grid[oldY][oldX] = '.'; // Clear old position
    this.grid[newY][newX] = this.player.sprite; // Set new position
    this.render();
  }

  // ... existing code ...
}

class Player {
  // ... existing code ...

  move(dx, dy) {
    const newX = this.x + dx;
    const newY = this.y + dy;

    // Check boundaries
    if (newX >= 0 && newX < this.game.grid[0].length && newY >= 0 && newY < this.game.grid.length) {
      const oldX = this.x;
      const oldY = this.y;

      this.x = newX;
      this.y = newY;

      this.game.updatePlayerPosition(oldX, oldY, this.x, this.y);
    }
  }
}

function handleKeyPress(event, player) {
  switch (event.key) {
    case 'ArrowLeft':
      player.move(-1, 0);
      break;
    case 'ArrowRight':
      player.move(1, 0);
      break;
    case 'ArrowUp':
      player.move(0, -1);
      break;
    case 'ArrowDown':
      player.move(0, 1);
      break;
    default:
      break;
  }
}

document.getElementById('play-button').addEventListener('click', () => {
  const game = new Game('game-container');
  const player = new Player(game);
  game.render();
  game.player = player; // Keeping a reference to the player within the game

  window.addEventListener('keydown', (event) => handleKeyPress(event, player));
});
```

This update includes the following changes and additions:

- **The `updatePlayerPosition` method in the `Game` class:** This method clears the old position of the player and updates the new one, then calls the `render` method to update the display.
- **The `move` method in the `Player` class:** This method updates the player's position based on the direction of movement while ensuring that the player does not go outside the grid boundaries.
- **The `handleKeyPress` function:** This function listens for arrow key presses and moves the player accordingly.

### Understanding the `move` Method

The `move` method takes two parameters, `dx` and `dy`, which represent the change in the x and y coordinates, respectively. This method first calculates the new potential position and then checks if the new position is within the grid boundaries. If it is, the player's position is updated, and the grid is refreshed to reflect the player's new location.

### Adding Event Listeners

In the previous code snippet, we attach an event listener to the window object to handle keydown events. When an arrow key is pressed, the `handleKeyPress` function is triggered, which then calls the `move` method on the player object with the appropriate direction parameters.

